{
  "title": "Observing Event-Driven Systems Using FastAPI in Python 3.12+",
  "summary": "This explainer provides a guide on how to leverage FastAPI, a modern web framework for building APIs with Python 3.12+, to observe event-driven systems. It covers creating an event-driven API, handling events, and utilizing WebSockets.",
  "key_points": [
    "Install FastAPI, Uvicorn, and AIOMultiprocessing.",
    "Create a FastAPI application with an instance of the FastAPI app class.",
    "Define routes for handling client requests and events.",
    "Implement WebSocket functionality using FastAPI's `WebSocket` class for real-time event communication between the server and clients.",
    "Demonstrate how to process incoming events in the `WebSocket` callback function.",
    "Explain how to run the application using Uvicorn with the appropriate settings for WebSockets."
  ],
  "code_examples": [
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "```\n\
import fastapi\nfastapi = FastAPI()\n\
ws = fastapi.WebSocket\n\
@fastapi.get('/')\n\ndef index():\n    return {'message': 'Welcome to the event-driven API!'}\n\nclass WebSocketHandler:\n    async def __init__(self, ws: WebSocket):\n        self.ws = ws\n    async def send_event(self, event_data):\n        await self.ws.send_text(json.dumps(event_data))\n    # Other methods for handling events go here...\n\n@ws('/websocket')\nasync def websocket_endpoint(websocket: WebSocket):\n    web_socket_handler = WebSocketHandler(websocket)\n    await web_socket_handler.handle()\n```"
    }
  ],
  "version_notes": [
    "This explainer is tailored to Python 3.12+ and FastAPI version 0.75.0.",
    "Ensure your environment has the latest updates for both Python and FastAPI."
  ],
  "caveats": [
    "Python 3.12 is not officially released yet, but this explainer aims to prepare you for its features when it becomes available.",
    "FastAPI's WebSocket functionality requires a compatible ASGI server like Uvicorn."
  ]
